{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"dc506ca1-c991-496c-b918-3b9a48c4b293","content":"Here's a step-by-step approach:\n\n### 1. Get a shell into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace` in the container\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find your process ID\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect the trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### Getting the file off the container\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-nettrace> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### Tips\n- If you can't install tools in the container, **mount `dotnet-trace` via a volume** or bake it into your image.\n- For **event-based CPU analysis**, use `--profile cpu-sampling` (default). For GC/allocation issues, use `--profile gc-collect`.\n- Alternatively, you can use **`dotnet-counters monitor`** first for a quick live view of CPU, GC, and thread pool stats before committing to a full trace.\n- Since you have **host admin access**, you can also capture an **ETW trace** with `PerfView` or `dotnet-trace` using the `--format speedscope` flag for browser-based analysis.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bb0134b8-699a-41b5-b68d-d9c24805722f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a troubleshooting/advisory question, not a code change request. I can answer this from my knowledge without needing to search the codebase.","outputTokens":439,"requestId":"680B:FBA15:A7FDC2F:B6F84BC:69FD3B30"},"id":"8745efa8-0c4d-4dbc-824b-60cd3e620c57","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:24:11.893Z","parentId":"e22fa7e8-d860-4330-bb3b-a7d952b69072"}
